WEBVTT

00:00.962 --> 00:04.125
Friends, welcome to Word on Fire Catholic Ministries.

00:04.686 --> 00:18.380
Word on Fire is an apostolate dedicated to the mission of evangelization, using media both old and new to share the faith on every continent and to facilitate an encounter with Christ and His Church.

00:19.121 --> 00:26.649
The efforts of Word on Fire engage the culture and bring the transformative power of God's Word where it is most needed.

00:26.709 --> 00:27.890
Today,

00:27.970 --> 00:35.982
We invite you to join Bishop Robert Barron as he preaches the gospel and shares the warmth and light of Christ with each one of us.

00:40.709 --> 00:41.390
Peace be with you.

00:41.430 --> 00:49.021
Friends, this Sunday, we're celebrating with the whole church the dedication of the great cathedral of Rome, the Lateran Basilica.

00:49.922 --> 00:55.090
You know, when you go to Rome, you can visit the four major basilicas, St. Peter's of course,

00:55.202 --> 01:03.731
St. Mary Major, St. Paul aside the walls, but you could argue very persuasively, the most important of the four is St. John Lanteran.

01:03.771 --> 01:04.271
Now, why?

01:04.952 --> 01:07.935
Well, because it's the sea church of the Bishop of Rome.

01:08.616 --> 01:22.610
So the pope lives near St. Peter's and St. Peter's is the grandest and we're all the great liturgies and so on are held, but it's not the sea church, meaning the church where the seat or the cothedra of the Bishop of Rome is situated.

01:22.690 --> 01:26.956
You can find that in the back in the apps of St. John Landerin.

01:27.537 --> 01:35.348
So really, if there's any one great temple of the Catholic church worldwide, it wouldn't be St. Peter's.

01:36.109 --> 01:38.312
It would be St. John Landerin.

01:38.332 --> 01:43.820
That's why the church puts a great stress on this feast day of the dedication of John Landerin.

01:43.840 --> 01:44.281
I love it.

01:44.301 --> 01:45.222
I've been there many times.

01:45.282 --> 01:48.146
We've filmed there for different things.

01:48.610 --> 01:59.304
Literally, as the pillars along the nave, you have these grand statues of all the apostles, the churches based upon the apostolic faith.

01:59.665 --> 02:05.112
Above the ball, the keynote over the main altar, there are the heads of St. Peter and Paul.

02:05.773 --> 02:10.940
And as I say, in the back of the church is the cothedra or the teaching chair of the pope.

02:11.040 --> 02:15.666
And so it is the great temple of Catholicism.

02:16.347 --> 02:18.290
And that's why the readings for today

02:18.562 --> 02:20.144
are all about the temple.

02:20.625 --> 02:25.772
And as you probably know, if you follow me at all and read things of mine, I love talking about the temple.

02:26.593 --> 02:32.381
The temple you could say is the master theme of the entire Bible.

02:32.942 --> 02:44.157
If you're looking for a symbol that kind of runs all the way through the scriptures, something that links together, everything from Genesis to Revelation, you could very plausibly say, it's the temple.

02:44.858 --> 02:45.139
Why?

02:45.780 --> 02:47.602
This place of right,

02:47.874 --> 02:54.824
This place where the people of God meet the Lord and they find union.

02:55.325 --> 02:59.290
Israel worshiping the Lord, God meeting his people.

02:59.851 --> 03:02.755
So the temple is a charged place.

03:03.316 --> 03:06.200
That's why I often quote 2nd chapter of Isaiah.

03:06.881 --> 03:09.304
Mount Zion, the true pole of the earth.

03:09.384 --> 03:11.607
Mount Zion meant the place where the temple is.

03:12.248 --> 03:14.512
There all the tribes go up.

03:15.132 --> 03:16.274
It's the magnetic place.

03:16.578 --> 03:20.082
center of the whole world, the temple, the temple.

03:21.223 --> 03:27.951
That's why the great authors and the great patriarchs and figures of the Bible are kind of obsessed with the temple.

03:29.032 --> 03:32.736
They're critical of it in many ways, and they extol it.

03:33.176 --> 03:34.097
Now why are they critical?

03:34.257 --> 03:38.062
Because it falls short of what it's supposed to be.

03:38.622 --> 03:42.066
Look at all the prophets, the major prophets, minor prophets, all of them.

03:42.722 --> 03:47.830
They tend to look at the temple with a kind of jaundiced eye, but again, it's not because they hate the temple.

03:48.170 --> 04:03.794
It's because they love the temple and they see it as a place, unfortunately, of corruption, where the worship of false gods has found its way, where the people are not oriented to God, but to other gods, and then they fall into disharmony, et cetera.

04:03.814 --> 04:06.018
And so the prophets raise their voices against it.

04:06.719 --> 04:11.346
No exception there is the prophet Ezekiel, and our first reading is from Ezekiel.

04:11.490 --> 04:13.173
Ezekiel was a prophet, yes indeed.

04:13.213 --> 04:15.336
He was also a temple priest.

04:16.217 --> 04:17.499
He knew all about the temple.

04:18.381 --> 04:23.228
And that's why he begins with this furious critique of the temple.

04:23.609 --> 04:36.468
There's no greater criticism in the Bible of the temple than in Ezekiel because he tells us that the Shekina, the glory of the Lord, has up and left the temple.

04:37.630 --> 04:40.274
I've said, maybe you've heard me before, I've written about it,

04:40.578 --> 04:51.592
It's one of the most devastating lines in the whole Bible that God's glory has up and left His temple, gone east over the Mount of Olives, left the temple.

04:53.114 --> 04:57.379
And we never hear in the Old Testament that it ever comes back.

04:59.181 --> 05:09.554
However, by the end of the book of the Prophet Ezekiel, and now we come to our first reading on this feast of John Lateran, the great temple of the Catholic Church, 47th chapter,

05:10.466 --> 05:12.810
Ezekiel has a kind of vision.

05:12.830 --> 05:22.965
Of one day when the Shaqeenah comes back, one day when the temple is restored, what will happen?

05:24.047 --> 05:27.412
Well, the people will be back in the attitude of right praise.

05:28.013 --> 05:35.785
But then in this gorgeous image, he sees water flowing out from beneath the threshold of the temple.

05:37.147 --> 05:39.250
And then as he continues to

05:39.426 --> 05:40.968
as this vision unfolds.

05:41.608 --> 05:57.406
He sees the water flowing from the southern side and now making its way into the countryside and now down to the dead sea and then making eventually the salty waters fresh.

05:58.428 --> 06:07.538
And then he envisions great trees growing along the side of the stream and the beauty of the trees and even their leaves are being used for medicine.

06:08.482 --> 06:09.604
What is this, everybody?

06:09.684 --> 06:17.094
But it's an image of the restored temple which amounts to the restored creation.

06:18.115 --> 06:20.839
You see, it's the book of Genesis here being re-envisioned.

06:21.620 --> 06:27.488
Genesis before the fall, God makes his beautifully constituted universe.

06:27.509 --> 06:30.192
It's destroyed, it's interrupted by sin.

06:30.633 --> 06:34.899
But when the temple is restored, God's creation will be restored.

06:35.339 --> 06:37.202
Now, my point is, in Ezekiel,

06:37.986 --> 06:48.121
You see the prophetic disdain for the temple, and you see in the richest way the prophetic love for the temple, both are on display.

06:49.183 --> 06:57.595
Okay, with Ezekiel haunting your mind, now turn to the gospel, which is from second chapter of St. John.

06:58.196 --> 07:02.342
St. John, like all the biblical authors, is obsessed practically with the temple.

07:03.624 --> 07:04.265
What do we hear?

07:05.326 --> 07:07.730
Jesus goes up to the temple.

07:09.890 --> 07:12.693
And he's horrified by what he sees.

07:13.734 --> 07:15.135
He's shocked by what he sees.

07:16.056 --> 07:21.702
It's all the merchants and the money changers, and it's the corruption of the temple.

07:21.722 --> 07:25.806
It's meant to be a house of prayer, but you've made it into this den of thieves.

07:27.228 --> 07:33.234
So Jesus, like all the prophets, calls down judgment upon the temple.

07:34.195 --> 07:37.138
In fact, he acts out the judgment upon the temple.

07:37.858 --> 07:44.325
overturning the tables and making the whip of cords, and he moves furiously through the temple, purifying it.

07:45.847 --> 07:52.394
There's all the prophetic disgust with the corruption of the temple, now on display.

07:53.355 --> 08:01.283
But then what he says, says the Jews answered and said to him, what sign can you show us to justify your doing all this?

08:02.124 --> 08:07.570
Jesus says, destroy this temple, and in three days I will

08:07.682 --> 08:08.323
Raise it up.

08:09.864 --> 08:12.527
There's the whole prophetic tradition of the Old Testament.

08:13.548 --> 08:14.449
Destroy this temple.

08:14.469 --> 08:16.472
I mean, this temple is under judgment.

08:18.193 --> 08:21.877
But in three days, I will raise it up.

08:21.897 --> 08:24.901
I will build a new temple.

08:25.041 --> 08:29.065
As Ezekiel envisioned, Jesus announces, I will build a new temple.

08:29.506 --> 08:30.807
Well, three days, what are you talking about?

08:30.827 --> 08:33.170
They say it's 47 years to build this.

08:33.550 --> 08:35.352
This was Herod's renovation of the temple.

08:36.513 --> 08:37.234
Three days.

08:38.146 --> 08:42.251
Well, John reminds us, he was speaking of the temple of his body.

08:42.992 --> 09:06.642
Okay, now, now, just a few, in John's account, Jesus does this very early in his ministry, but when he comes to the cross on Golgothar and Calvary, on top of Mount Zion, in view of the temple, Jesus makes this great sacrificial offering, uh-huh, the cross is

09:06.850 --> 09:09.793
expressing fully what the temple was meant to be.

09:09.853 --> 09:21.185
And then the dead Christ is approached by a Roman soldier with a spear and he pierces the side and out comes blood and water.

09:23.568 --> 09:28.693
No one who knew the Bible is going to miss the symbolic power of that.

09:29.895 --> 09:36.722
In the water flowing from the side of Christ, we see fulfilled Ezekiel's

09:36.866 --> 09:46.002
prophecy that from the side of the renewed temple, water will flow forth for the renewal of the world.

09:47.324 --> 09:49.107
Ah, there it is.

09:50.149 --> 09:54.316
Jesus' body is now the true temple.

09:55.177 --> 09:58.183
It's not so much the building in Jerusalem that matters.

09:59.365 --> 10:00.146
In a way,

10:00.418 --> 10:06.927
Jesus' judgment anticipates its destruction in the year 70 AD when the Romans raised it to the ground.

10:07.327 --> 10:15.258
You know, the wailing wall today that I visited there with found it deeply moving is the retaining wall of that temple.

10:15.278 --> 10:16.400
That's all that's left of it.

10:17.321 --> 10:20.786
But see, we say it's not that building in Jerusalem that matters so much.

10:21.687 --> 10:29.618
Rather, it's the body of the crucified and risen Lord, which is now, listen, the place of right praise

10:30.466 --> 10:39.698
That's why every mass, every mass, the Eucharist, the source and summer of the Christian life is a re-presentation of the sacrifice of Jesus.

10:40.298 --> 10:42.401
We eat his body and drink his blood.

10:42.461 --> 10:55.517
And from the side of the sacrificed Christ comes indeed the water that renews all of creation.

10:55.538 --> 10:59.122
I see everybody, that's what the temple means for us.

11:01.218 --> 11:08.848
And every church building is meant to be evocative of this great truth.

11:10.791 --> 11:15.177
You know, when I was coming of age, we kind of understressed church buildings.

11:15.237 --> 11:18.121
We put a huge stress on the community as the church.

11:18.962 --> 11:20.484
Fair enough, sure it is, of course it is.

11:22.166 --> 11:28.274
But the troubles, we kind of underplayed the importance of these temples in which we worship.

11:29.314 --> 11:38.984
because the church building itself is meant to be a symbolic evocation of the body of Christ.

11:40.526 --> 11:45.191
In it, we're supposed to see the renewed temple.

11:46.772 --> 11:47.593
How wonderful, everybody.

11:47.613 --> 11:55.922
Look, when we finish Mass, and so we've listened to the word of Christ in the Liturgy of the Word,

11:56.898 --> 12:00.222
We've seen the re-presentation of the sacrifice of Christ.

12:00.682 --> 12:05.688
We've eaten his body and we've drunk his blood, and then we're sent forth.

12:08.070 --> 12:25.970
In a way, like the water flowing from the side of Christ, we flow out of that church building, meant to become great Catholics in the world, crystallifying whatever it is that we touch.

12:26.818 --> 12:35.929
We're journalists, we're writers, we're teachers, we're politicians, we're financiers, we're investors, whatever it is, whatever it is.

12:37.491 --> 12:44.080
We're meant to be now the water that flows forth from the side of Christ for the renewal of the world.

12:44.580 --> 12:55.474
And that's why, if I can glance at reading number two, Paul says, brothers and sisters, you are God's building.

12:56.386 --> 13:03.353
Don't you know that you're the temple of God and that the spirit of God dwells in you?

13:03.393 --> 13:04.814
Okay.

13:06.035 --> 13:09.338
We come forth as members of the mystical body of Christ.

13:09.859 --> 13:18.627
We come forth from the church, the temple meant to be symbolic of him, so as to transfigure the world.

13:20.008 --> 13:26.034
I think, friends, the church wants us to think about all of this as we look

13:26.306 --> 13:35.721
intently at this one particular church in Rome, St. John Lateran, the Sea Church of the Bishop of Rome, the Great Temple of Catholicism.

13:35.801 --> 13:47.079
As we look at that, we're meant to see this deep truth about the temple, about Christ, and then finally about us and our role in the world.

13:48.361 --> 13:49.042
And God bless you.

13:53.410 --> 13:57.024
And thank you for listening to this week's homily from Bishop Robert Barron.

13:57.446 --> 14:02.546
For more resources from Bishop Barron, please visit wordonfire.org.

